ich, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Cholsey, Berkshire, England":"Cholsey, Berkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lord","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>laford</i>, <i>louerd</i>, <i>lord</i> ‘lord, master’ (Old English <i>hlāford</i>), perhaps given to a someone who played the part of the lord or master of ceremonies in festival games.","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as a translation of the main element of Gaelic <b>Ó Tighearnaigh</b> (see   Tierney  ) and <b>Mac Thighearnáin</b> (see   McKiernan  ).","Americanized form of French <b>Laure</b>, a variant of the personal name   Laur   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Tierney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamon, John Patrick, Brigid, Clodagh, Kieran, Michael Sean, Siobhan.","Irish: shortened form of <b>O'Tierney</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Tíghearnaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Tighearnach</i>’, a byname meaning ‘lord, master’. The Gaelic name is sometimes ‘translated’ as English   Lord  . Compare   Tiernan  ."]},{"name":"Lords","meanings":["English: variant of   Lord  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Cheng, Jing, Kam Fung, Wai Shing, Wing, Yali, Yuk.","Chinese:","variant Romanization of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Ou","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ying, Ching, Heng, Hong, Jia, Kuang Yu, Li-Ching, Cho, Chong, Chung, Sa.  Southeast Asian Lichun, Ming, Quan, Roeun, Sokhom, Chau, Hai, Leang, Ly, Nhanh, Phan, Pho, Tha.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 歐, meaning ‘to sing someone's praise’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the placename Dong Ou (東甌), a fief (in present-day Wenzhou in Zhejiang province) which was granted to Yao in 192  BC . It is said that Yao was a descendant of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the placename Ou Yu (歐餘), the name of a fief (located in present-day Zhejiang province) that was granted to Ti, the second son of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 區, originally denoting an ancient vessel for measurement in ancient Chinese: from the personal name of <i>Ou Zhizi</i> (歐治子), an expert sword-maker who lived during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). Some of his descendants inherited <i>Ou</i> (歐) as their surname, simplifying the Chinese character 歐 to 區."]}]},{"name":"Stampes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>sta(u)mpere</i>, recorded only in the sense ‘one who treads grapes’ but possibly also denoting one who crushed or pounded stuff or who threshed grain.","German: nickname for someone working at a crushing mill (see   Stamp   1), or a habitational name for someone from any of the places called Stampe or Stampen."],"variants":[{"name":"Stamp","meanings":["German: metonymic occupational name for someone who worked at a crushing mill, from Middle Low German <i>stamp</i> ‘pestle, crusher’.","English: variant of   Stamps  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":19,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Lord of Stampes was born in 1363, in Ipswich, Suffolk, England, his father, John d'Estampes I, was 24 and his mother, d'Estampes, was 24. He had at least 1 son with Stampes. He died in 1393, in Cholsey, Berkshire, England, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1363–1393":"1363–1393","1363–Female":"1363–Surnud","1385–1409":"1385–1409","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","1363":"1363","1385":"1385","1340":"1340","1393":"1393","1382":"1382","1409":"1409","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","Ipswich, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Ipswich, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cholsey, Berkshire, England":"Cholsey, Berkshire, England"},"fi":{"1363–1393":"1363–1393","1363–Female":"1363–Kuollut","1385–1409":"1385–1409","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1340–Female":"1340–Kuollut","1363":"1363","1385":"1385","1340":"1340","1393":"1393","1382":"1382","1409":"1409","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","Ipswich, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Ipswich, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cholsey, Berkshire, England":"Cholsey, Berkshire, England"},"fr":{"1363–1393":"1363–1393","1363–Female":"1363–Décédée","1385–1409":"1385–1409","1340–Male":"1340–Décédé","1340–Female":"1340–Décédée","1363":"1363","1385":"1385","1340":"1340","1393":"1393","1382":"1382","1409":"1409","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, Angleterre","Ipswich, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Ipswich, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Cholsey, Berkshire, England":"Cholsey, Berkshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque John Lord of Stampes est né en 1363, à Ipswich, Suffolk, Angleterre, son p